# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: process-calculus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] In computer science, the **ambient calculus** is a process calculus devised by Luca Cardelli and Andrew D.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] Gordon in 1998, and used to describe and theorise about concurrent systems that include *mobility*.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] Here *mobility* means both computation carried out on mobile devices (*i.e.* networks that have a dynamic topology), and mobile computation (*i.e.* executable code that is able to move around the network).
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] The ambient calculus provides a unified framework for modeling both kinds of mobility.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] It is used to model interactions in such concurrent systems as the Internet.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] Since its inception, the ambient calculus has grown into a family of closely related ambient calculi.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] The fundamental primitive of the ambient calculus is the **ambient**.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] An ambient is informally defined as a *bounded* place in which computation can occur.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] The notion of boundaries is considered key to representing mobility, since a boundary defines a contained computational agent that can be moved in its entirety.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] Computation is represented as the crossing of boundaries, *i.e.* the movement of ambients.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] The ambient calculus provides a reduction semantics that formally defines what the results of these operations are.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] Communication *within* (*i.e.* local to) an ambient is anonymous and asynchronous.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] Output actions release names or capabilities into the surrounding ambient.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] Input actions capture a value from the ambient, and bind it to a variable.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] *Non-local* I/O can be represented in terms of these local communications actions by a variety of means.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] One approach is to use mobile “messenger” agents that carry a message from one ambient to another (using the capabilities described above).
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] Another approach is to emulate channel-based communications by modeling a channel in terms of ambients and operations on those ambients.
[src:process-calculus/ambient-calculus] The three basic ambient primitives, namely **in**, **out**, and **open** are expressive enough to simulate name-passing channels in the π-calculus.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] In mathematics, **coalgebras** or **cogebras** are structures that are dual (in the category-theoretic sense of reversing arrows) to unital associative algebras.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The axioms of unital associative algebras can be formulated in terms of commutative diagrams.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Turning all arrows around, one obtains the axioms of coalgebras.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Every coalgebra, by (vector space) duality, gives rise to an algebra, but not in general the other way.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] In finite dimensions, this duality goes in both directions (see below).
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Coalgebras occur naturally in a number of contexts (for example, representation theory, universal enveloping algebras and group schemes).
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] There are also **F-coalgebras**, with important applications in computer science.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] One frequently recurring example of coalgebras occurs in representation theory, and in particular, in the representation theory of the rotation group.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] A primary task, of practical use in physics, is to obtain combinations of systems with different states of angular momentum and spin.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] For this purpose, one uses the Clebsch–Gordan coefficients.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Given two systems $A,B$ with angular momenta $j_{A}$ and $j_{B}$ , a particularly important task is to find the total angular momentum $j_{A}+j_{B}$ given the combined state $|A\rangle \otimes |B\rangle$ .
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] This is provided by the total angular momentum operator, which extracts the needed quantity from each side of the tensor product.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The word "external" appears here, in contrast to the "internal" tensor product of a tensor algebra.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] A tensor algebra comes with a tensor product (the internal one); it can also be equipped with a second tensor product, the "external" one, or the coproduct, having the form above.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] That they are two different products is emphasized by recalling that the internal tensor product of a vector and a scalar is just simple scalar multiplication.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The external product keeps them separated.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] For this example, J can be taken to be one of the spin representations of the rotation group, with the fundamental representation being the common-sense choice.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] This coproduct can be lifted to all of the tensor algebra, by a simple lemma that applies to free objects: the tensor algebra is a free algebra, therefore, any homomorphism defined on a subset can be extended to the entire algebra.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Examining the lifting in detail, one observes that the coproduct behaves as the shuffle product, essentially because the two factors above, the left and right $\mathbf {j}$ must be kept in sequential order during products of multiple angular momenta (rotations are not commutative).
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The peculiar form of having the $\mathbf {j}$ appear only once in the coproduct, rather than (for example) defining $\mathbf {j} \mapsto \mathbf {j} \otimes \mathbf {j}$ is in order to maintain linearity: for this example, (and for representation theory in general), the coproduct *must* be linear.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] As a general rule, the coproduct in representation theory is reducible; the factors are given by the Littlewood–Richardson rule.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The formal definition of the coalgebra, below, abstracts away this particular special case, and its requisite properties, into a general setting.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] In the first diagram, *C* ⊗ (*C* ⊗ *C*) is identified with (*C* ⊗ *C*) ⊗ *C*; the two are naturally isomorphic.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Similarly, in the second diagram the naturally isomorphic spaces *C*, *C* ⊗ *K* and *K* ⊗ *C* are identified.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The first diagram is the dual of the one expressing associativity of algebra multiplication (called the **coassociativity** of the comultiplication); the second diagram is the dual of the one expressing the existence of a multiplicative identity.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Accordingly, the map Δ is called the **comultiplication** (or **coproduct**) of *C* and ε is the **counit** of *C*.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Take an arbitrary set *S* and form the *K*-vector space *C* = *K*(*S*) with basis *S*, as follows.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The elements of this vector space *C* are those functions from *S* to *K* that map all but finitely many elements of *S* to zero; identify the element *s* of *S* with the function that maps *s* to 1 and all other elements of *S* to 0.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] By linearity, both Δ and ε can then uniquely be extended to all of *C*.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The vector space *C* becomes a coalgebra with comultiplication Δ and counit ε.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] As a second example, consider the polynomial ring *K*[*X*] in one indeterminate *X*.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Again, because of linearity, this suffices to define Δ and ε uniquely on all of *K*[*X*].
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Now *K*[*X*] is both a unital associative algebra and a coalgebra, and the two structures are compatible.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Objects like this are called bialgebras, and in fact most of the important coalgebras considered in practice are bialgebras.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Examples of coalgebras include the tensor algebra, the exterior algebra, Hopf algebras and Lie bialgebras.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Unlike the polynomial case above, none of these are commutative.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Therefore, the coproduct becomes the shuffle product, rather than the divided power structure given above.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The shuffle product is appropriate, because it preserves the order of the terms appearing in the product, as is needed by non-commutative algebras.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The singular homology of a topological space forms a graded coalgebra whenever the Künneth isomorphism holds, e.g. if the coefficients are taken to be a field.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] In this situation, (*C*, Δ, ε) is a coalgebra known as **trigonometric coalgebra**.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] For a locally finite poset *P* with set of intervals *J*, define the **incidence coalgebra** *C* with *J* as basis.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The intervals of length zero correspond to points of *P* and are group-like elements.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] In finite dimensions, the duality between algebras and coalgebras is closer: the dual of a finite-dimensional (unital associative) algebra is a coalgebra, while the dual of a finite-dimensional coalgebra is a (unital associative) algebra.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] In general, the dual of an algebra may not be a coalgebra.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The key point is that in finite dimensions, (*A* ⊗ *A*)∗ and *A*∗ ⊗ *A*∗ are isomorphic.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] To distinguish these: in general, algebra and coalgebra are dual *notions* (meaning that their axioms are dual: reverse the arrows), while for finite dimensions, they are also dual *objects* (meaning that a coalgebra is the dual object of an algebra and conversely).
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] If *A* is a *finite-dimensional* unital associative *K*-algebra, then its *K*-dual *A*∗ consisting of all *K*-linear maps from *A* to *K* is a coalgebra.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The multiplication of *A* can be viewed as a linear map *A* ⊗ *A* → *A*, which when dualized yields a linear map *A*∗ → (*A* ⊗ *A*)∗.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] In the finite-dimensional case, (*A* ⊗ *A*)∗ is naturally isomorphic to *A*∗ ⊗ *A*∗, so this defines a comultiplication on *A*∗.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The counit of *A*∗ is given by evaluating linear functionals at 1.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] When working with coalgebras, a certain notation for the comultiplication simplifies the formulas considerably and has become quite popular.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Here it is understood that the sums have the same number of terms, and the same lists of values for $c_{(1)}$ and $c_{(2)}$ , as in the previous sum for $\Delta (c)$ .
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Whenever a variable with lowered and parenthesized index is encountered in an expression of this kind, a summation symbol for that variable is implied.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Contrary to what this naming convention suggests the group-like elements do not always form a group and in general they only form a set.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The group-like elements of a Hopf algebra do form a group.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] A **primitive element** is an element *x* that satisfies Δ(*x*) = *x* ⊗ 1 + 1 ⊗ *x*.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The primitive elements of a Hopf algebra form a Lie algebra.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The composition of two coalgebra morphisms is again a coalgebra morphism, and the coalgebras over *K* together with this notion of morphism form a category.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] In that case, the quotient space *C*/*I* becomes a coalgebra in a natural fashion.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] A subspace *D* of *C* is called a **subcoalgebra** if Δ(*D*) ⊆ *D* ⊗ *D*; in that case, *D* is itself a coalgebra, with the restriction of ε to *D* as counit.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The kernel of every coalgebra morphism *f* : *C*1 → *C*2 is a coideal in *C*1, and the image is a subcoalgebra of *C*2.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] The common isomorphism theorems are valid for coalgebras, so for instance *C*1/ker(*f*) is isomorphic to im(*f*).
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] If *A* is a finite-dimensional unital associative *K*-algebra, then *A*∗ is a finite-dimensional coalgebra, and indeed every finite-dimensional coalgebra arises in this fashion from some finite-dimensional algebra (namely from the coalgebra's *K*-dual).
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Under this correspondence, the commutative finite-dimensional algebras correspond to the cocommutative finite-dimensional coalgebras.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] So in the finite-dimensional case, the theories of algebras and of coalgebras are dual; studying one is equivalent to studying the other.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] However, relations diverge in the infinite-dimensional case: while the *K*-dual of every coalgebra is an algebra, the *K*-dual of an infinite-dimensional algebra need not be a coalgebra.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Every coalgebra is the sum of its finite-dimensional subcoalgebras, something that is not true for algebras.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Abstractly, coalgebras are generalizations, or duals, of finite-dimensional unital associative algebras.
[src:process-calculus/coalgebra] Corresponding to the concept of representation for algebras is a **corepresentation** or comodule.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modal logics are formal systems that include unary operators such as $\Diamond$ and $\Box$ , representing possibility and necessity respectively.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For instance the modal formula $\Diamond P$ can be read as "possibly P " while $\Box P$ can be read as "necessarily P ".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In the standard relational semantics for modal logic, formulas are assigned truth values relative to a *possible world*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] A formula's truth value at one possible world can depend on the truth values of other formulas at other *accessible* possible worlds.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In particular, $\Diamond P$ is true at a world if P is true at *some* accessible possible world, while $\Box P$ is true at a world if P is true at *every* accessible possible world.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] A variety of proof systems exist which are sound and complete with respect to the semantics one gets by restricting the accessibility relation.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For instance, the deontic modal logic **D** is sound and complete if one requires the accessibility relation to be serial.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] While the intuition behind modal logic dates back to antiquity, the first modal axiomatic systems were developed by C.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The now-standard relational semantics emerged in the mid twentieth century from work by Arthur Prior, Jaakko Hintikka, and Saul Kripke.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Recent developments include alternative topological semantics such as neighborhood semantics as well as applications of the relational semantics beyond its original philosophical motivation.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Such applications include game theory, moral and legal theory, web design, multiverse-based set theory, and social epistemology.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modal logic differs from other kinds of logic in that it uses modal operators such as $\Box$ and $\Diamond$ .
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The former is conventionally read aloud as "necessarily", and can be used to represent notions such as moral or legal obligation, knowledge, historical inevitability, among others.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The latter is typically read as "possibly" and can be used to represent notions including permission, ability, compatibility with evidence.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] While well-formed formulas of modal logic include non-modal formulas such as $P\land Q$ , it also contains modal ones such as $\Box (P\land Q)$ , $P\land \Box Q$ , $\Box (\Diamond P\land \Diamond Q)$ , and so on.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Thus, the language ${\mathcal {L}}$ of basic propositional logic can be defined recursively as follows.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] If $\phi$ is a formula of ${\mathcal {L}}$ , then $\neg \phi$ is too.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] If $\phi$ and $\psi$ are formulas of ${\mathcal {L}}$ , then $\phi \land \psi$ is too.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] If $\phi$ is a formula of ${\mathcal {L}}$ , then $\Diamond \phi$ is too.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] If $\phi$ is a formula of ${\mathcal {L}}$ , then $\Box \phi$ is too.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modal operators can be added to other kinds of logic by introducing rules analogous to #4 and #5 above.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modal predicate logic is one widely used variant which includes formulas such as $\forall x\Diamond P(x)$ .
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In systems of modal logic where $\Box$ and $\Diamond$ are duals, $\Box \phi$ can be taken as an abbreviation for $\neg \Diamond \neg \phi$ , thus eliminating the need for a separate syntactic rule to introduce it.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] However, separate syntactic rules are necessary in systems where the two operators are not interdefinable.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Common notational variants include symbols such as $[K]$ and $\langle K\rangle$ in systems of modal logic used to represent knowledge and $[B]$ and $\langle B\rangle$ in those used to represent belief.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] These notations are particularly common in systems which use multiple modal operators simultaneously (multi-modal logic).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For instance, a combined epistemic-deontic logic could use the formula $[K]\langle D\rangle P$ read as "I know P is permitted".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Systems of modal logic can include infinitely many modal operators distinguished by indices, i.e. $\Box _{1}$ , $\Box _{2}$ , $\Box _{3}$ , and so on.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The standard semantics for modal logic is called the *relational semantics*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In this approach, the truth of a formula is determined relative to a point which is often called a *possible world*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For a formula that contains a modal operator, its truth value can depend on what is true at other accessible worlds.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Thus, the relational semantics interprets formulas of modal logic using models defined as follows.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The set W is often called the *universe*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The binary relation R is called an accessibility relation, and it controls which worlds can "see" each other for the sake of determining what is true.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For example, $wRu$ means that the world u is accessible from world w .
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] That is to say, the state of affairs known as u is a live possibility for w .
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Finally, the function V is known as a valuation function.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] It determines which atomic formulas are true at which worlds.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] According to this semantics, a formula is *necessary* with respect to a world w if it holds at every world that is accessible from w .
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] It is *possible* if it holds at some world that is accessible from w .
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Possibility thereby depends upon the accessibility relation R , which allows us to express the relative nature of possibility.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For example, we might say that given our laws of physics it is not possible for humans to travel faster than the speed of light, but that given other circumstances it could have been possible to do so.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The choice of accessibility relation alone can sometimes be sufficient to guarantee the truth or falsity of a formula.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For instance, consider a model ${\mathfrak {M}}$ whose accessibility relation is reflexive.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Because the relation is reflexive, we will have that ${\mathfrak {M}},w\models P\rightarrow \Diamond P$ for any $w\in G$ regardless of which valuation function is used.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For this reason, modal logicians sometimes talk about *frames*, which are the portion of a relational model excluding the valuation function.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The different systems of modal logic are defined using *frame conditions*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The Euclidean property along with reflexivity yields symmetry and transitivity.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] (The Euclidean property can be obtained, as well, from symmetry and transitivity.) Hence if the accessibility relation *R* is reflexive and Euclidean, *R* is provably symmetric and transitive as well.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Hence for models of S5, *R* is an equivalence relation, because *R* is reflexive, symmetric and transitive.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] We can prove that these frames produce the same set of valid sentences as do the frames where all worlds can see all other worlds of *W* (*i.e.*, where *R* is a "total" relation).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] This gives the corresponding *modal graph* which is total complete (*i.e.*, no more edges (relations) can be added).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] We can drop the accessibility clause from the latter stipulation because in such total frames it is trivially true of all *w* and *u* that *w R u*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] But this does not have to be the case in all S5 frames, which can still consist of multiple parts that are fully connected among themselves but still disconnected from each other.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] All of these logical systems can also be defined axiomatically, as is shown in the next section.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For example, in S5, the axioms $P\implies \Box \Diamond P$ , $\Box P\implies \Box \Box P$ and $\Box P\implies P$ (corresponding to *symmetry*, *transitivity* and *reflexivity*, respectively) hold, whereas at least one of these axioms does not hold in each of the other, weaker logics.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modal logic has also been interpreted using topological structures.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For instance, the *Interior Semantics* interprets formulas of modal logic as follows.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] A *topological model* is a tuple $\mathrm {X} =\langle X,\tau ,V\rangle$ where $\langle X,\tau \rangle$ is a topological space and V is a valuation function which maps each atomic formula to some subset of X .
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Topological approaches subsume relational ones, allowing non-normal modal logics.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The extra structure they provide also allows a transparent way of modeling certain concepts such as the evidence or justification one has for one's beliefs.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Topological semantics is widely used in recent work in formal epistemology and has antecedents in earlier work such as David Lewis and Angelika Kratzer's logics for counterfactuals.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The first formalizations of modal logic were axiomatic.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Numerous variations with very different properties have been proposed since C.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Lewis began working in the area in 1912.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Hughes and Cresswell (1996), for example, describe 42 normal and 25 non-normal modal logics.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Zeman (1973) describes some systems Hughes and Cresswell omit.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modern treatments of modal logic begin by augmenting the propositional calculus with two unary operations, one denoting "necessity" and the other "possibility".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Lewis, much employed since, denotes "necessarily *p*" by a prefixed "box" (□*p*) whose scope is established by parentheses.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Likewise, a prefixed "diamond" (◇*p*) denotes "possibly *p*".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Hence □ and ◇ form a dual pair of operators.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The weakest normal modal logic, named "*K*" in honor of Saul Kripke, is simply the propositional calculus augmented by □, the rule **N**, and the axiom **K**.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] *K* is weak in that it fails to determine whether a proposition can be necessary but only contingently necessary.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] That is, it is not a theorem of *K* that if □*p* is true then □□*p* is true, i.e., that necessary truths are "necessarily necessary".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] If such perplexities are deemed forced and artificial, this defect of *K* is not a great one.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In any case, different answers to such questions yield different systems of modal logic.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Adding axioms to *K* gives rise to other well-known modal systems.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] One cannot prove in *K* that if "*p* is necessary" then *p* is true.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The commonly employed system *S5* simply makes all modal truths necessary.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For example, if *p* is possible, then it is "necessary" that *p* is possible.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Also, if *p* is necessary, then it is necessary that *p* is necessary.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Other systems of modal logic have been formulated, in part because *S5* does not describe every kind of modality of interest.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] More complex calculi have been applied to modal logic to achieve generality.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Analytic tableaux provide the most popular decision method for modal logics.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modalities of necessity and possibility are called *alethic* modalities.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] They are also sometimes called *special* modalities, from the Latin *species*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modal logic was first developed to deal with these concepts, and only afterward was extended to others.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For this reason, or perhaps for their familiarity and simplicity, necessity and possibility are often casually treated as *the* subject matter of modal logic.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Moreover, it is easier to make sense of relativizing necessity, e.g. to legal, physical, nomological, epistemic, and so on, than it is to make sense of relativizing other notions.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In classical modal logic, therefore, the notion of either possibility or necessity may be taken to be basic, where these other notions are defined in terms of it in the manner of De Morgan duality.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Intuitionistic modal logic treats possibility and necessity as not perfectly symmetric.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For example, suppose that while walking to the convenience store we pass Friedrich's house, and observe that the lights are off.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] On the way back, we observe that they have been turned on.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Something is physically, or nomically, possible if it is permitted by the laws of physics.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For example, current theory is thought to allow for there to be an atom with an atomic number of 126, even if there are no such atoms in existence.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In contrast, while it is logically possible to accelerate beyond the speed of light, modern science stipulates that it is not physically possible for material particles or information.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Philosophers debate if objects have properties independent of those dictated by scientific laws.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For example, it might be metaphysically necessary, as some who advocate physicalism have thought, that all thinking beings have bodies and can experience the passage of time.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Saul Kripke has argued that every person necessarily has the parents they do have: anyone with different parents would not be the same person.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Metaphysical possibility has been thought to be more restricting than bare logical possibility (i.e., fewer things are metaphysically possible than are logically possible).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] However, its exact relation (if any) to logical possibility or to physical possibility is a matter of dispute.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Philosophers also disagree over whether metaphysical truths are necessary merely "by definition", or whether they reflect some underlying deep facts about the world, or something else entirely.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] A person, Jones, might reasonably say *both*: (1) "No, it is *not* possible that Bigfoot exists; I am quite certain of that"; *and*, (2) "Sure, it's *possible* that Bigfoots could exist".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] What Jones means by (1) is that, given all the available information, there is no question remaining as to whether Bigfoot exists.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] By (2) he makes the *metaphysical* claim that it is *possible for* Bigfoot to exist, *even though he does not*: there is no physical or biological reason that large, featherless, bipedal creatures with thick hair could not exist in the forests of North America (regardless of whether or not they do).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] From the other direction, Jones might say, (3) "It is *possible* that Goldbach's conjecture is true; but also *possible* that it is false", and *also* (4) "if it *is* true, then it is necessarily true, and not possibly false".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] It is worthwhile to observe that Jones is not necessarily correct: It is possible (epistemically) that Goldbach's conjecture is both true and unprovable.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Epistemic possibilities also bear on the actual world in a way that metaphysical possibilities do not.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Metaphysical possibilities bear on ways the world *might have been,* but epistemic possibilities bear on the way the world *may be* (for all we know).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Suppose, for example, that I want to know whether or not to take an umbrella before I leave.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] If you tell me "it is *possible that* it is raining outside" – in the sense of epistemic possibility – then that would weigh on whether or not I take the umbrella.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] But if you just tell me that "it is *possible for* it to rain outside" – in the sense of *metaphysical possibility* – then I am no better off for this bit of modal enlightenment.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Some features of epistemic modal logic are in debate.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For example, if *x* knows that *p*, does *x* know that it knows that *p*?
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] That is to say, should □*P* → □□*P* be an axiom in these systems?
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] It has been questioned whether the epistemic and alethic modalities should be considered distinct from each other.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The criticism states that there is no real difference between "the truth in the world" (alethic) and "the truth in an individual's mind" (epistemic).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] An investigation has not found a single language in which alethic and epistemic modalities are formally distinguished, as by the means of a grammatical mood.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Temporal logic is an approach to the semantics of expressions with tense, that is, expressions with qualifications of when.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Some expressions, such as '2 + 2 = 4', are true at all times, while tensed expressions such as 'John is happy' are only true sometimes.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In temporal logic, tense constructions are treated in terms of modalities, where a standard method for formalizing talk of time is to use *two* pairs of operators, one for the past and one for the future (P will just mean 'it is presently the case that P').
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] There are then at least three modal logics that we can develop.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Or we can trade these operators to deal only with the future (or past).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The operators **F** and **G** may seem initially foreign, but they create normal modal systems.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] We can combine the above operators to form complex statements.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For example, **P***P* → □**P***P* says (effectively), *Everything that is past and true is necessary*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] It seems reasonable to say that possibly it will rain tomorrow, and possibly it will not; on the other hand, since we cannot change the past, if it is true that it rained yesterday, it cannot be true that it may not have rained yesterday.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] It seems the past is "fixed", or necessary, in a way the future is not.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] This is sometimes referred to as accidental necessity.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] But if the past is "fixed", and everything that is in the future will eventually be in the past, then it seems plausible to say that future events are necessary too.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Similarly, the problem of future contingents considers the semantics of assertions about the future: is either of the propositions 'There will be a sea battle tomorrow', or 'There will not be a sea battle tomorrow' now true?
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Considering this thesis led Aristotle to reject the principle of bivalence for assertions concerning the future.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Additional binary operators are also relevant to temporal logics (see Linear temporal logic).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Versions of temporal logic can be used in computer science to model computer operations and prove theorems about them.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In one version, ◇*P* means "at a future time in the computation it is possible that the computer state will be such that *P* is true"; □*P* means "at all future times in the computation P will be true".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In another version, ◇*P* means "at the immediate next state of the computation, *P* might be true"; □*P* means "at the immediate next state of the computation, *P* will be true".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] These differ in the choice of Accessibility relation.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] (*P* always means "*P* is true at the current computer state".) These two examples involve nondeterministic or not-fully-understood computations; there are many other modal logics specialized to different types of program analysis.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Each one naturally leads to slightly different axioms.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Likewise talk of morality, or of obligation and norms generally, seems to have a modal structure.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The difference between "You must do this" and "You may do this" looks a lot like the difference between "This is necessary" and "This is possible".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Such logics are called *deontic*, from the Greek for "duty".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Deontic logics commonly lack the axiom **T** semantically corresponding to the reflexivity of the accessibility relation in Kripke semantics: in symbols, $\Box \phi \to \phi$ .
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Interpreting □ as "it is obligatory that", **T** informally says that every obligation is true.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For example, if it is obligatory not to kill others (i.e. killing is morally forbidden), then **T** implies that people actually do not kill others.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Instead, using Kripke semantics, we say that though our own world does not realize all obligations, the worlds accessible to it do (i.e., **T** holds at these worlds).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] These worlds are called *idealized* worlds.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] *P* is obligatory with respect to our own world if at all idealized worlds accessible to our world, *P* holds.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Though this was one of the first interpretations of the formal semantics, it has recently come under criticism.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] One other principle that is often (at least traditionally) accepted as a deontic principle is *D*, $\Box \phi \to \Diamond \phi$ , which corresponds to the seriality (or extendability or unboundedness) of the accessibility relation.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] It is an embodiment of the Kantian idea that "ought implies can".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] When we try to formalize ethics with standard modal logic, we run into some problems.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Suppose that we have a proposition *K*: you have stolen some money, and another, *Q*: you have stolen a small amount of money.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Now suppose we want to express the thought that "if you have stolen some money, it ought to be a small amount of money".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] But (1) and *K* together entail □*Q*, which says that it ought to be the case that you have stolen a small amount of money.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] This surely is not right, because you ought not to have stolen anything at all.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] And (2) does not work either: If the right representation of "if you have stolen some money it ought to be a small amount" is (2), then the right representation of (3) "if you have stolen some money then it ought to be a large amount" is $\Box (K\to (K\land \lnot Q))$ .
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Now suppose (as seems reasonable) that you ought not to steal anything, or $\Box \lnot K$ .
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] But then we can deduce $\Box (K\to (K\land \lnot Q))$ via $\Box (\lnot K)\to \Box (K\to K\land \lnot K)$ and $\Box (K\land \lnot K\to (K\land \lnot Q))$ (the contrapositive of $Q\to K$ ); so sentence (3) follows from our hypothesis (of course the same logic shows sentence (2)).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] But that cannot be right, and is not right when we use natural language.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Telling someone they should not steal certainly does not imply that they should steal large amounts of money if they do engage in theft.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modal logics may be extended to fuzzy form with calculi in the class of fuzzy Kripke models.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modal logics may also be enhanced via *base-extension semantics* for the classical propositional systems.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Intuitionistic modal logics are used in different areas of application, and they have often risen from different sources.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The areas include the foundations of mathematics, computer science and philosophy.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In these approaches, often modalities are added to intuitionistic logic to create new intuitionistic connectives and to simulate the monadic elements of intuitionistic first order logic.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In the most common interpretation of modal logic, one considers "logically possible worlds".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] If a statement is true in all possible worlds, then it is a necessary truth.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] If a statement happens to be true in our world, but is not true in all possible worlds, then it is a contingent truth.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] A statement that is true in some possible world (not necessarily our own) is called a possible truth.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Under this "possible worlds idiom", to maintain that Bigfoot's existence is possible but not actual, one says, "There is some possible world in which Bigfoot exists; but in the actual world, Bigfoot does not exist".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] However, it is unclear what this claim commits us to.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Are we really alleging the existence of possible worlds, every bit as real as our actual world, just not actual?
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Saul Kripke believes that 'possible world' is something of a misnomer – that the term 'possible world' is just a useful way of visualizing the concept of possibility.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For him, the sentences "you could have rolled a 4 instead of a 6" and "there is a possible world where you rolled a 4, but you rolled a 6 in the actual world" are not significantly different statements, and neither commit us to the existence of a possible world.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] David Lewis, on the other hand, made himself notorious by biting the bullet, asserting that all merely possible worlds are as real as our own, and that what distinguishes our world as *actual* is simply that it is indeed our world – *this* world.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] That position is a major tenet of "modal realism".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Some philosophers decline to endorse any version of modal realism, considering it ontologically extravagant, and prefer to seek various ways to paraphrase away these ontological commitments.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Robert Adams holds that 'possible worlds' are better thought of as 'world-stories', or consistent sets of propositions.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Thus, it is possible that you rolled a 4 if such a state of affairs can be described coherently.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Computer scientists will generally pick a highly specific interpretation of the modal operators specialized to the particular sort of computation being analysed.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In place of "all worlds", you may have "all possible next states of the computer", or "all possible future states of the computer".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modal logics have begun to be used in areas of the humanities such as literature, poetry, art and history.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In the philosophy of religion, modal logics are commonly used in arguments for the existence of God.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The basic ideas of modal logic date back to antiquity.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Aristotle developed a modal syllogistic in Book I of his *Prior Analytics* (ch.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] 8–22), which Theophrastus attempted to improve.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] There are also passages in Aristotle's work, such as the famous sea-battle argument in *De Interpretatione* §9, that are now seen as anticipations of the connection of modal logic with potentiality and time.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The earliest formal system of modal logic was developed by Avicenna, who ultimately developed a theory of "temporally modal" syllogistic.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Modal logic as a self-aware subject owes much to the writings of the Scholastics, in particular William of Ockham and John Duns Scotus, who reasoned informally in a modal manner, mainly to analyze statements about essence and accident.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In the 19th century, Hugh MacColl made innovative contributions to modal logic, but did not find much acknowledgment.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Lewis founded modern modal logic in a series of scholarly articles beginning in 1912 with "Implication and the Algebra of Logic".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Lewis was led to invent modal logic, and specifically strict implication, on the grounds that classical logic grants paradoxes of material implication such as the principle that a falsehood implies any proposition.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] This work culminated in his 1932 book *Symbolic Logic* (with C.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Langford), which introduced the five systems *S1* through *S5*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] After Lewis, modal logic received little attention for several decades.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Nicholas Rescher has argued that this was because Bertrand Russell rejected it.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Barcan (later Ruth Barcan Marcus) developed the first axiomatic systems of quantified modal logic — first and second order extensions of Lewis' *S2*, *S4*, and *S5*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Arthur Norman Prior warned her to prepare well in the debates concerning quantified modal logic with Willard Van Orman Quine, because of bias against modal logic.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The contemporary era in modal semantics began in 1959, when Saul Kripke (then only an 18-year-old Harvard University undergraduate) introduced the now-standard Kripke semantics for modal logics.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] These are commonly referred to as "possible worlds" semantics.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Prior had previously corresponded at some length.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Kripke semantics is basically simple, but proofs are eased using semantic-tableaux or analytic tableaux, as explained by E.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Prior created modern temporal logic, closely related to modal logic, in 1957 by adding modal operators [F] and [P] meaning "eventually" and "previously".
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Vaughan Pratt introduced dynamic logic in 1976.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] In 1977, Amir Pnueli proposed using temporal logic to formalise the behaviour of continually operating concurrent programs.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Flavors of temporal logic include propositional dynamic logic (PDL), (propositional) linear temporal logic (LTL), computation tree logic (CTL), Hennessy–Milner logic, and *T*.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] The mathematical structure of modal logic, namely Boolean algebras augmented with unary operations (often called modal algebras), began to emerge with J.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] McKinsey's 1941 proof that *S2* and *S4* are decidable, and reached full flower in the work of Alfred Tarski and his student Bjarni Jónsson (Jónsson and Tarski 1951–52).
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] This work revealed that *S4* and *S5* are models of interior algebra, a proper extension of Boolean algebra originally designed to capture the properties of the interior and closure operators of topology.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] Texts on modal logic typically do little more than mention its connections with the study of Boolean algebras and topology.
[src:process-calculus/modal-logic] For a thorough survey of the history of formal modal logic and of the associated mathematics, see Robert Goldblatt (2006).
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:process-calculus/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] Milner was born in Yealmpton, near Plymouth, England into a military family.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] He gained a King's Scholarship to Eton College in 1947, and was awarded the Tomline Prize (the highest prize in Mathematics at Eton) in 1952.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] Subsequently, he served in the Royal Engineers, attaining the rank of Second Lieutenant.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] He then enrolled at King's College, Cambridge, graduating in 1957.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] He returned to Cambridge as the head of the Computer Laboratory in 1995 from which he eventually stepped down, although he was still at the laboratory.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] From 2009, Milner was a Scottish Informatics & Computer Science Alliance Advanced Research Fellow and held (part-time) the chair of computer science at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] Milner died of a heart attack on 20 March 2010 in Cambridge.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] His wife, Lucy, died shortly before he did.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] Milner is generally regarded as having made three major contributions to computer science.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] He developed Logic for Computable Functions (LCF), one of the first tools for automated theorem proving.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] The language he developed for LCF, ML, was the first language with polymorphic type inference, type-safe exception handling, and an automatically inferred type system, using algorithm W.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] Milner also developed two theoretical frameworks for analyzing concurrent systems, the calculus of communicating systems (CCS), and its successor, the π-calculus.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] At the time of his death, he was working on bigraphs, a formalism for ubiquitous computing subsuming CCS and the π-calculus.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] He is also credited for rediscovering the Hindley–Milner type system.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] He was made a Fellow of the Royal Society and a Distinguished Fellow of the British Computer Society in 1988.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] Milner received the ACM Turing Award in 1991.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] In 1994 he was inducted as a Fellow of the ACM.
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] In 2004, the Royal Society of Edinburgh awarded Milner with a Royal Medal for his "bringing about public benefits on a global scale".
[src:process-calculus/robin-milner] The Royal Society Milner Award and the ACM SIGPLAN Robin Milner Young Researcher Award are both named after him.
[src:process-calculus/trace-theory] In mathematics and computer science, **trace theory** aims to provide a concrete mathematical underpinning for the study of concurrent computation and process calculi.
[src:process-calculus/trace-theory] The underpinning is provided by an algebraic definition of the free partially commutative monoid or trace monoid, or equivalently, the history monoid, which provides a concrete algebraic foundation, analogous to the way that the free monoid provides the underpinning for formal languages.
[src:process-calculus/trace-theory] The power of trace theory stems from the fact that the algebra of dependency graphs (such as Petri nets) is isomorphic to that of trace monoids, and thus, one can apply both algebraic formal language tools, as well as tools from graph theory.
